               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18440205-name-1289" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18440205-name-1289" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440205-name-1289" type="surname" value="BELLINGER"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440205-name-1289" type="given" value="DANIEL"></interp>DANIEL BELLINGER</persName>
                  </hi>. I live on board the <hi rend="italic">William Murray</hi>, in the East India Docks. On the night of the 3rd of Feb. I went into the Steam-ship public-house—I placed my great-coat on the back of a chair—in a few minutes I heard some person say, "That man has taken a coat"—I then heard another voice say, "Yes, and he did not bring one in with him"—I them</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184402050192"></xptr>
               <p>turned, and missed my coat—I went out directly, and saw the prisoner with it under his arm—I brought him back, and asked if he knew what he bad done—he made no reply—I had a silk handkerchief and gloves in the pocket.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Prisoner. Q.</hi> Was I drunk or sober? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> I think he had been drinking—I cannot tell whether he intended to steal it—when I asked him, he said, "I don't care anything about the coat, give me a pipe of tobacco."</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Prisoner's Defence.</hi> I had several glasses of grog, and then they asked me to help a man on shore with his clothes to the Steam-ship public-house; I recollect nothing of the coat; I found myself next morning in the station.</p>
               <p>
